# Lab 10 - OSPF Routing

## Objective

To configure OSPF (Open Shortest Path First) between two routers and establish dynamic routing for communication between different networks.

---

## Devices Used

- 2 Cisco 1941 Routers
- 2 Cisco 2960 Switches
- 2 PCs

---

## Network Topology

- R1
- R2
- SW1
- SW2
- PC1
- PC2

Two LANs were connected through two routers. OSPF Area 0 was configured to dynamically exchange routing information.

---

## IP Addressing

### LAN 1

Network: 192.168.1.0/24

Gateway: 192.168.1.1

### LAN 2

Network: 192.168.2.0/24

Gateway: 192.168.2.1

### Router-to-Router Link

Network: 10.0.0.0/30

R1: 10.0.0.1

R2: 10.0.0.2

---

## OSPF Configuration

### R1

```text
router ospf 1
router-id 1.1.1.1

network 192.168.1.0 0.0.0.255 area 0
network 10.0.0.0 0.0.0.3 area 0
```

### R2

```text
router ospf 1
router-id 2.2.2.2

network 192.168.2.0 0.0.0.255 area 0
network 10.0.0.0 0.0.0.3 area 0
```

---

## Verification

The following commands were used to verify the configuration:

```text
show ip ospf neighbor

show ip route

show ip protocols

ping
```

The OSPF neighbor relationship was successfully established, the routing table displayed OSPF-learned routes (`O`), and end-to-end connectivity was verified using the ping command.

